Having opened just a few weeks ago, La Piazza Locale brings the 2nd VPN-certified Neapolitan pizza to downtown Phoenix.
The first thing I thought when I found this place was, "What, don't we have enough excellent pies downtown?
"  But we had to try it anyways.
My friend went with Rocco, and I went with the special of the day Don Matteo (smoked butternut squash puree as the sauce, with speck and mozarella).
My first observation was that the crust had the soupiness that a real Napoletana pizza should have.
The crust was perfect.
This is knife-and-fork pizza, and if you think their crust is too soggy, you're wrong.
The smoked butternut was phenomenal.
I'm not sure that's a real authentic ingredient for Neapolitan pizza, but it was probably one of the top three pies I have ever eaten.
My friend's Rocco was pretty good, too, but the Don Matteo was definitely at a whole different level.
My only real complaint about this place was that the music was a little too loud and too trendy.
When dining, I don't like it when the music is too noticeable.
I usually prefer restaurants not to be too trendy, but everything else about the restaurant was great, so I can let this pass.
Locale is now on my short list of best pies in the Valley.
It's not as good as Bianco, but it's top tier.

Downtown Phoenix has become a pizza battlefield in 2013, with no less than 4 quality authentic pizzerias dotting the landscape.
On the west side of downtown is Cibo.
On the east side of downtown is Bianco.
In north central downtown is Pomo.
And now just caddie corner from Cityscape is La Piazza al Forno's newest location.
For the record I've been to La Piazza al Forno in Glendale before, but was interested to see what kind of twist they'd put on their new location.
My girlfriend and I came on a Wednesday night.
The place was pretty dead as there were no games at the ballpark or the arena nor any concerts or shows going on.
Probably explained the light turnout.
Still, we were welcomed and served promptly and enthusiastically by our waitress.
The place is somewhat similar to their Glendale location in that its dark and modern inside.
The Glendale location has a little bit more of a joint feel to it (probably because they have outdoor seating whereas this location doesn't).
The music playing in the background I suppose could be classified as hipster or trendy.
Cool I guess if you're into that sort of thing.
They were having a nice promotion for the evening.
Order two pizzas and you get a free dessert.
Sold.
My girlfriend got the Salciccia e Friarelle with sausage, broccoli, olive oil, and smoked mozzarella.
They aren't kidding when they say smoked as you can pick up the smoke flavor immediately.
Its a nice white pizza in that it doesn't have tomato sauce, but it has a very clean flavor to it.
I got the Lasagne Ah Pizz with mozzarella, ricotta (I love cheese), sausage, tomato sauce, and basil.
Had every bit the richness I expected and more and complimented my red wine very nicely.
For dessert, we split the Angioletti con Nutella.
Delicious dish perfect for split with two or more people, but I'll be honest, I was hoping for much more nutella than we got.
Still, it was free so no major complaints.
All totaled, a glass of wine, a beer, two pizzas and dessert plus tip totaled about $55.
Pretty on par price wise with the other high end pizza spots downtown, though as I said we got a deal on dessert.
Now that I've tried each of the big four pizza joints downtown, I have to admit that Locale is probably the weakest of the four.
Which is not to say they're bad.
They have a great product and no doubt already have a following among the downtown lunch crowd and event goers.
And Downtown Glendale should feel grateful to have their flagship location.
But with so many high quality pizzerias in the downtown area already, Locale will need to step up their game to compete with the other three pizzerias with big reputations.
If I had to rank the big four Downtown Phoenix pizzerias in order of preference it would be: 1.
Pomo 2.
Cibo 3.
Bianco 4.
Locale

